ZCTA to county info lookup table

r package noncensus

Seemed to be easy to use, but only mapped one ZCTA to one county. Not used now.

# get county name and county code for each row.
library(noncensus)
data(zip_codes)
data(counties)
counties = data.table(counties)
zip_codes = data.table(zip_codes)
counties[, state_fips:= as.character(state_fips)]
counties[, county_fips:= as.character(county_fips)]
zip_codes[, fips := sprintf("%05d", fips)]
# add combined fips for county
counties[, fips := paste0(state_fips, county_fips)]
# merge county info to zipcode rows, now we can match zip to county fips
setkey(counties, fips)
setkey(zip_codes, fips)
zip_counties = merge(zip_codes, counties)
setnames(zip_counties, "zip", "Zip")
setkey(zip_counties, Zip)

The official 2010 ZCTA relationship file.

  • POPPT ~ Calculated 2010 Population for the relationship record
  • ZPOP ~ 2010 Population of the 2010 ZCTA
  • ZPOPPCT ~ The Percentage of Total Population of the 2010 ZCTA represented by the record. Some area have 0 or 1 population and 0 or 100 ratio.

There are 33120 unique ZCTAs in 44410 rows, 9036 ZCTAs in them covered more than 1 county, in which 76% have a population distribution higher than 80/20. So we just select the county of most share of population for each ZCTA to work as a simple temporary workaround. The better method will be geocoding each specific address to county.

county_fips = fread("data/Geo/2010 FIPS.txt", sep=',', header = TRUE, 
                    stringsAsFactors=FALSE, 
                    colClasses=list(character=c("StateFP","CountyFP"))) # keep leading 0s
zip_county_fips = fread("data/Geo/zcta_county_rel_10.txt", sep=',', header = TRUE,
                   stringsAsFactors=FALSE,
                   colClasses=list(character=c("ZCTA5","STATE","COUNTY","GEOID")))
# we will call State fips + county fips as countyGEOID in all related data
setnames(zip_county_fips, "GEOID", "countyGEOID")
county_fips[, countyGEOID := paste0(StateFP, CountyFP)]

Data coverage by ZCTA, county, state

  • fire incident coverage, chart and map
  • NFIRS reporting dept coverage, chart and map

  • imputation for non-reporting area

  • joint data together, find common high coverage areas.

Turned out each zipcode was visited for 16 times in average. maybe we could use these data locally. Use them globally have too much variation, but use them to compare in local area, may introduce some weight and information.

# ----- RC home visits ------------------------------------------------------------------
# coverage_dataname is the list of each item with zip, then extend to county fips
coverage_RC_home = RC_home_visit[, .(.I, Date, Zip)] 
setnames(coverage_RC_home, "Zip", "ZCTA5")
# merge county, state information to prepare future aggregation
coverage_RC_home = merge(coverage_RC_home, zip_county_single, by = "ZCTA5")
zip_coverage_RC_home = coverage_RC_home[, .(value = .N), by = ZCTA5] 
county_coverage_RC_home = coverage_RC_home[, .(value = .N), by = countyGEOID]
state_coverage_RC_home = coverage_RC_home[, .(value = .N), by = State]
# choropleth for state
data(state.regions)
state_regions = data.table(state.regions)
setnames(state_regions, "abb", "State") # this will be reused for other state choropleths
state_choropleth(merge(state_regions, state_coverage_RC_home, by = "State"),
                 title      = "Red Cross Smoke Alarm Home Visits per State",
                 legend     = "visits",
                 num_colors = 4)

# choropleth for county
data(county.regions)
county_regions = data.table(county.regions)
setnames(county_regions, "county.fips.character", "countyGEOID")
# need to coerce as data frame since data.table will use different merge function
county_choropleth(as.data.frame(merge(county_regions, county_coverage_RC_home, 
                                      by = "countyGEOID")),
                 title      = "Red Cross Smoke Alarm Home Visits per County",
                 legend     = "visits",
                 num_colors = 4)
